00:46:08,140 --> 00:46:11,820
and that is that it is just simply the greatest intellectual

1043
00:46:11,820 --> 00:46:14,220
quest of all time.

1044
00:46:14,220 --> 00:46:16,300
We could fight about cosmology.

1045
00:46:16,300 --> 00:46:18,340
I'm not going to fight with you about anything else.

1046
00:46:18,340 --> 00:46:20,020
I don't think there's any contest.

1047
00:46:20,020 --> 00:46:22,700
It's the greatest intellectual quest of all time.

1048
00:46:22,700 --> 00:46:24,700
And that's why I'm in it, and that's why I hope

1049
00:46:24,700 --> 00:46:27,020
it'll be fun for you.

1050
00:46:27,020 --> 00:46:29,820
OK, that was the Y. How are we going

1051
00:46:29,820 --> 00:46:31,660
to study the human brain?

1052
00:46:31,660 --> 00:46:33,060
So here's this thing.

1053
00:46:33,060 --> 00:46:34,740
How are we going to figure out how it works?

1054
00:46:34,740 --> 00:46:36,020
It's kind of daunting.

1055
00:46:36,020 --> 00:46:38,060
It's not totally obvious.

1056
00:46:38,060 --> 00:46:39,580
The first thing to realize is that there

1057
00:46:39,580 --> 00:46:42,420
are lots of levels of organization in this thing,

1058
00:46:42,420 --> 00:46:44,620
and hence, lots of ways of studying it.

1059
00:46:44,620 --> 00:46:47,100
We could look at molecules and their interactions,

1060
00:46:47,100 --> 00:46:49,340
lots of people in this building do that.

1061
00:46:49,340 --> 00:46:52,460
We could look at properties of individual neurons.

1062
00:46:52,460 --> 00:46:54,780
We could look at circuits of neurons interacting

1063
00:46:54,780 --> 00:46:56,500
with each other.

1064
00:46:56,500 --> 00:46:58,620
We could look at entire brain regions

1065
00:46:58,620 --> 00:47:00,340
and what their functions are.

1066
00:47:00,340 --> 00:47:03,060
We could look at networks of multiple brain regions

1067
00:47:03,060 --> 00:47:05,700
interacting with each other.

1068
00:47:05,700 --> 00:47:08,980
And so all of those things are possible.

1069
00:47:08,980 --> 00:47:10,860
But actually, what we're going to do in the course

1070
00:47:10,860 --> 00:47:13,060
is none of those things in particular.

1071
00:47:13,060 --> 00:47:15,860
Instead, we're going to ask a somewhat different question.

1072
00:47:15,860 --> 00:47:20,340
And that question is, how does the brain give rise to the mind?

1073
00:47:20,340 --> 00:47:22,420
And to understand that question, we're

1074
00:47:22,420 --> 00:47:25,380
going to do more at this level and less at the upper levels.

1075
00:47:25,900 --> 00:47:28,220
OK?

1076
00:47:28,220 --> 00:47:30,980
So to answer this question, we need to start with the mind.

1077
00:47:30,980 --> 00:47:32,380
We need to, if we're going to understand,

1078
00:47:32,380 --> 00:47:34,420
how does this thing produce a mind,

1079
00:47:34,420 --> 00:47:36,300
we need to first figure out, what is a mind?

1080
00:47:36,300 --> 00:47:38,500
What do we know about minds?

1081
00:47:38,500 --> 00:47:40,620
OK?

1082
00:47:40,620 --> 00:47:43,140
And so we need to start with the various mental functions

1083
00:47:43,140 --> 00:47:46,460
that minds carry out, things like perception, vision,

1084
00:47:46,460 --> 00:47:50,900
hearing, aspects of cognition, like understanding language,

1085
00:47:50,900 --> 00:47:54,580
thinking about people, thinking about things, et cetera.

1086
00:47:54,580 --> 00:47:55,820
OK?

1087
00:47:55,820 --> 00:47:59,740
And so for each mental function, what we're going to do in here

1088
00:47:59,740 --> 00:48:03,060
is start by trying to understand how it works in minds,

1089
00:48:03,060 --> 00:48:05,180
as well as we can, or what it is that we're

1090
00:48:05,180 --> 00:48:07,460
trying to understand that minds can do.

1091
00:48:07,460 --> 00:48:09,260
What is computed and how?

1092
00:48:09,260 --> 00:48:11,220
And then we're going to look at its brain basis

1093
00:48:11,220 --> 00:48:12,660
and try to figure out what we can

1094
00:48:12,660 --> 00:48:15,140
figure out about how that mental function is implemented

1095
00:48:15,140 --> 00:48:16,380
in a brain.

1096
00:48:16,380 --> 00:48:19,140
So the first question we'll ask for all of these domains

1097
00:48:19,140 --> 00:48:22,820
is, is there specialized machinery to do that thing?

1098
00:48:22,820 --> 00:48:24,380
And then we'll ask, what information

1099
00:48:24,380 --> 00:48:27,140
is represented in the relevant parts of the brain?

1100
00:48:27,140 --> 00:48:30,060
And when is that information represented?

1101
00:48:30,060 --> 00:48:31,220
OK?

1102
00:48:31,220 --> 00:48:32,780
And how?

1103
00:48:32,780 --> 00:48:35,500
OK, so how are we going to answer those questions?

1104
00:48:35,500 --> 00:48:38,060
Well, there's lots and lots of methods in our field.

1105
00:48:38,060 --> 00:48:38,860
OK?

1106
00:48:38,860 --> 00:48:42,140
And so the first set of methods, if we want to understand minds,

1107
00:48:42,140 --> 00:48:44,740
the first set of methods are the basic stuff

1108
00:48:44,740 --> 00:48:46,900
of cognitive science, psychophysics.

1109
00:48:46,900 --> 00:48:49,580
That means showing people visual stimuli

1110
00:48:49,580 --> 00:48:52,420
or playing them sounds and asking them what they see or hear.

1111
00:48:52,420 --> 00:48:55,700
Nice and low-tech, but lots has been learned from those methods.

1112
00:48:55,700 --> 00:48:57,740
You collect reaction time and accuracy,

1113
00:48:57,740 --> 00:48:59,660
and it's amazing how much you can learn

1114
00:48:59,660 --> 00:49:03,620
from these methods that have been around for 100 years or more.

1115
00:49:03,620 --> 00:49:06,580
Perceptual illusions are similarly very informative

1116
00:49:06,580 --> 00:49:08,300
about how minds work.

1117
00:49:08,300 --> 00:49:12,260
Now, let me say an important thing that arises here.

1118
00:49:12,260 --> 00:49:14,220
Last year was the first time I taught this course,

